GLM Model

Quasi-Poisson model since the number of deaths right-skew distributed

hist(hurricane$alldeaths, ylab = "Frequency", xlab = "Number of deaths")

and Var(Y) >> E[Y] (3.80786^{4} > 44.1

Observational study design: - Outcome: Number of Death - Determinant: Femininity of the Hurricane Name - Confounders: Year, Min of pressure, Wind, Amount of damages normalized at 2015. We consider the following glm:

\[g(\mu)=\alpha+f_1(\mbox{mf})+f_2(\mbox{year})+f_3(\mbox{min})+f_4(\mbox{wind})+f_5(\mbox{ndam15})\]

where:

\[\mbox{alldeaths} \sim quasiPoisson(\lambda=g^{-1}(X\beta),\phi)\] where \(\lambda\) is mean parameter and \(\phi\) is estimated to deal with overdispersion (scale). Use set the \(\log()\) as link function \(g()\)

Some considerations:
- limited sample size: n=94
- model with 5 predictors and 1 intercept

We consider a simple additive regression model like the follwing one:

\[g(\mu)=\alpha+\beta_1 mf+ \beta_2 year+\beta_3 min+\beta_4 wind+\beta_5 ndam15\] The coefficient \(\beta_1\) expresses the increase of the log-death due to a 1-point increase in the \(mf\) variable. The results of a Poisson regression models are commonly expressed in terms of Incidence Rate Ratio (IRR) just by exponentiation of the coefficients. (IRR=\(\exp(\beta_1)\)).

Theoretical model

We know in advance that the number of deaths depends on the strength of the hurricane (combination of min and wind) and of high population density and relative damages (ndam15). In addition the year is an important confounder for two reasons:
- 1) the alternating of the male/female name to an hurricane began in 1978 (https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/aboutnames_history.shtml)
- 2) The year is a key factor for assessing the spread of information and its use in the general population over the year.

ggplot(hurricane, aes(x = year, y = masfem, col = gender_mf)) + ylab("Degree of femininity") +
    geom_point(size = 3) + xlab("Year") + labs(col = "Gender")

MULTIVERSE ANALYSIS

All the four confounders are continuous. In addition to the identity, we decide to explore for each confounders the following transformations:
- Square Root (\(\sqrt(x)\));
- Log (\(\sqrt(x)\));
- Second order polynomial (\(x+x^2\)).

########################################### possible specifications:
combinations_matrix = expand.grid(list(c("min", "sqrt(min)", "log(min)", "poly(min,2)"),
    c("wind", "sqrt(wind)", "log(wind)", "poly(wind,2)"), c("year", "sqrt(year)",
        "log(year)", "poly(year,2)"), c("ndam15", "sqrt(ndam15)", "log(ndam15)",
        "poly(ndam15,2)")))

combinations = apply(combinations_matrix, 1, paste, collapse = "+")

Then we combine all the transformations in \(4^4=256\) specifications

##################### one list of formulas for each comparison of interest:
formulas1 = sapply(combinations, function(cmb) paste0("alldeaths ~ masfem +", cmb))
mod1 = glm(as.formula(formulas1[1]), data = hurricane, family = quasipoisson())
mods1 = lapply(formulas1, function(frml) update(mod1, formula. = as.formula(frml)))

Using the function() we apply the PIMA procedure to the list of models inside the mods1 list.

res1 = pima(mods1, tested_coeffs = c("masfem"), n_flips = 5000, score_type = "standardized",
    seed = 167)
names(res1)
[1] "Tspace"        "summary_table" "mods"          "info"         
[5] "tested_coeffs"

The output is composed by:
- Tspace: output table of sign_flip score testing
- summary_table: overall results
- mods: 256 models estimated (one for each specification)
- info: specifications info (auxiliary object)

Pick up a model

Since the overall p-value is lower than <0.05, we can select among the estimated models a significant model

sel_model <- which.min(res1$summary_table$p.adj)
summary(mods1[[sel_model]])

Call:
glm(formula = alldeaths ~ masfem + min + sqrt(wind) + year +
